items.title: Dabur: A bigger rural footprint, a wider product basket key growth levers
items.description: Urban demand has bottomed out and expected to pick up once food inflation stabilises

items.title: Can Indian startups grab the AI opportunity to threaten entrenched IT market leaders?
items.description: Indian startups in the AI space are still struggling to find themselves. In the first half of 2024, the funding for generative artificial intelligence (AI) startups in India was just around $760 million. That number has to go up if the country is to catch this wave. Otherwise, like it happened with the cloud revolution, we will have to be content with collecting the crumbs

items.title: Kaynes Technology Q2: Impressive growth, but cash flow remains anaemic
items.description: The company continues to execute well; it has been upping the outlook in the last few quarters, beating industry trends

items.title: Larsen & Toubro: Better recovery in H2 likely, aided by higher order inflows
items.description: A general slowdown in the construction and engineering segment in H1 hit the company. However, higher capex and likely availability of workers and other resources are expected to make H2 stronger.

items.title: E-commerce and Q-commerce: Revolutionising retail and consumer convenience
items.description: E-commerce and q-commerce are transforming traditional retail by enhancing convenience for consumers and boosting sales for local vendors. Despite concerns about their impact on kirana stores, these innovations create job opportunities and foster entrepreneurship, benefiting the entire value chain
